Exerpts:
ENHL commissioner Gary Bettman has announced he will reevaluate the league's use of Pride-themed warmups after several players refused to wear rainbow-colored jerseys created for the event.

Airing the development in a rink-side interview in Ottawa Monday, Bettman cited players' personal beliefs in his decision to reexamine the practice.

'This is the first time we've experienced that, and I think it's something that we're going to have to evaluate in the offseason,' Bettman told CTV News. 'This is one issue where players for a variety of reasons may not feel comfortable wearing the uniform as a form of endorsement.'

A handful of players have objected to participating in pregame warmups that included Pride-themed jerseys, most recently Florida's Eric and Marc Staal last week. On March 23, the Chicago Blackhawks decided against having players wear Pride-themed warmup jerseys for their upcoming Pride night, citing an anti-gay law in Russia.

The Staal brothers and San Jose's James Reimer ‚Äî who are Canadian ‚Äî and Philadelphia's Ivan Provorov, who is Russian, all pointed to their religious beliefs for refusing to take part in warmups.

'We carry no judgement on how people choose to live their lives, and believe that all people should be welcome in all aspects of the game of hockey,' Eric and Marc Staal said in a statement. 'Having said that, we feel that by us wearing a Pride jersey, it goes against our Christian beliefs.'

Nashville Predators prospect Luke Prokop, who in 2021 made history as the first player signed to an NHL contract to come out as gay, called the Pride night incidents a 'step back' for hockey.

Bettman addressed the issue last month.

'Whether or not you choose to embrace and make a statement on behalf of a cause affirmatively, if you choose not to do that, it doesn't necessarily make you a bigot,' Bettman said last month. 'I'm sure you don't endorse every single charity that solicits you, and you don't participate in every social cause. You pick and choose the ones that are important to you.'

The Canucks are still planning to hold a pride night on Friday. It was not clear if players would wear Pride jerseys in warmups, as the teams have done in the past.
